    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-05-05T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-05-05T18:00:00-05:00" n="367"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d367">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European War 1939/2564: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Winant</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-05-05T19:00:00-04:00"
                            >May 5, 1944—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>3611. The Department is willing to accept the text of the proposed tripartite
                    statement on the satellite countries as revised by the British Cabinet and
                    transmitted in your 3628 May 3 with only one modification. In order to preserve
                    the thought of satellite responsibility and <pb facs="0620" n="606"
                        xml:id="pg_606"/> at the same time avoid undue discouragement we would
                    prefer the following language for numbered paragraph 3: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“3. While these nations cannot escape their responsibility for having
                            participated in the war at the side of Nazi Germany, the longer they
                            continue at war in collaboration with Germany the more disastrous will
                            be the consequences to them and the more rigorous will be the terms
                            which will be imposed upon them.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Please ask the British Foreign Office if it is agreeable to the foregoing
                    modification of the text as revised by the British Cabinet and state that it is
                    being submitted in this form to Moscow for Soviet approval. As soon as British
                    and Soviet approval has been received the Department will again fix a date for
                    release using the same hours as previously arranged.<note n="63"
                        xml:id="d367fn63">Following agreement to this revision of paragraph 3 among
                        the three Governments, the statement was made public on May 12; for text,
                        see Department of State <hi rend="italic">Bulletin</hi>, May 13, 1944, p.
                        425.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Repeated to Moscow.<note n="64" xml:id="d367fn64">As telegram 1120.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
